				Challenge: "device1-challenge-base64",
				KeyHandle: "device1-keyhandle-base64",
				AppID:     "https://teleport.example.com",
			},
			{
				Version:   "U2F_V2",
				Challenge: "device2-challenge-base64",
				KeyHandle: "device2-keyhandle-base64",
				AppID:     "https://teleport.example.com",
			},
		},
	}

	// Marshal to JSON (what the REST API returns)
	jsonData, err := json.Marshal(challenge)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to marshal challenge: %v", err)
	}

	fmt.Printf("JSON output: %s\n", string(jsonData))

	// FIRST CRITICAL TEST: All challenges must be in the JSON
	var jsonObj map[string]interface{}
	err = json.Unmarshal(jsonData, &jsonObj)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to unmarshal JSON to map: %v", err)
	}

	// Check top-level fields (for backwards compat with pre-6.0 clients)
	if _, hasVersion := jsonObj["version"]; !hasVersion {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Top-level version field missing (pre-6.0 compat broken)")
	}
	if _, hasChallenge := jsonObj["challenge"]; !hasChallenge {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Top-level challenge field missing (pre-6.0 compat broken)")
	}
	if _, hasKeyHandle := jsonObj["keyHandle"]; !hasKeyHandle {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Top-level keyHandle field missing (pre-6.0 compat broken)")
	}

	// Check challenges array
	challengesRaw, hasArray := jsonObj["challenges"]
	if !hasArray {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: JSON output missing 'challenges' field - multi-device challenges lost!")
	}

	challengesArray, ok := challengesRaw.([]interface{})
	if !ok {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Challenges field should be an array, got %T", challengesRaw)
	}

	if len(challengesArray) != 2 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Expected 2 challenges for 2 registered devices, but only found %d in JSON", len(challengesArray))
	}

	fmt.Println("✓ JSON marshaling preserves all challenges")
	return nil
}

// testEmbeddedPointerFlattening tests the embedded pointer behavior during JSON
// marshaling, which is the root cause of the bug.
func testEmbeddedPointerFlattening() error {
	// This test verifies that Go's JSON marshaling correctly handles
	// embedded pointer fields

	type inner struct {
		Field1 string `json:"field1"`
		Field2 string `json:"field2"`
	}

	type outer struct {
		*inner
		Field3 string `json:"field3"`
	}

	// When inner is not nil, its fields get promoted to top level
	obj := &outer{
		inner: &inner{Field1: "value1", Field2: "value2"},
		Field3: "value3",
	}

	data, err := json.Marshal(obj)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to marshal: %v", err)
	}

	var result map[string]interface{}
	err = json.Unmarshal(data, &result)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to unmarshal: %v", err)
	}

	// All fields should be at top level
	if result["field1"] != "value1" {
		return fmt.Errorf("embedded field1 not at top level")
	}
	if result["field2"] != "value2" {
		return fmt.Errorf("embedded field2 not at top level")
	}
	if result["field3"] != "value3" {
		return fmt.Errorf("direct field3 not at top level")
	}

	fmt.Println("✓ Embedded pointer fields are correctly flattened")
	return nil
}

// testChallengeFieldPreservation tests that when unmarshaling, both the
// embedded fields AND the Challenges array are preserved.
func testChallengeFieldPreservation() error {
	jsonInput := `{
		"version": "U2F_V2",
		"challenge": "device1-challenge",
		"keyHandle": "device1-keyhandle",
		"appId": "https://teleport.example.com",
		"challenges": [
			{
				"version": "U2F_V2",
				"challenge": "device1-challenge",
				"keyHandle": "device1-keyhandle",
				"appId": "https://teleport.example.com"
			},
			{
				"version": "U2F_V2",
				"challenge": "device2-challenge",
				"keyHandle": "device2-keyhandle",
				"appId": "https://teleport.example.com"
			}
		]
	}`

	var challenge U2FAuthenticateChallengeSimulated
	err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(jsonInput), &challenge)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to unmarshal challenge: %v", err)
	}

	// Check embedded fields were unmarshaled
	if challenge.AuthenticateChallengeSimulated == nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Embedded field not populated")
	}
	if challenge.AuthenticateChallengeSimulated.Challenge != "device1-challenge" {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Embedded challenge field has wrong value")
	}

	// CRITICAL TEST: Check that Challenges array was unmarshaled
	if len(challenge.Challenges) == 0 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Challenges field not populated during unmarshaling")
	}
	if len(challenge.Challenges) != 2 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Should have 2 challenges for 2 devices, got %d", len(challenge.Challenges))
	}

	// Verify each challenge is unique
	if challenge.Challenges[0].Challenge != "device1-challenge" {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: First challenge has wrong value")
	}
	if challenge.Challenges[1].Challenge != "device2-challenge" {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Second challenge has wrong value")
	}
	if challenge.Challenges[0].KeyHandle == challenge.Challenges[1].KeyHandle {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Each device should have a unique key handle")
	}

	fmt.Println("✓ Challenges field preserved during marshaling/unmarshaling")
	return nil
}

// testBackwardsCompatibility tests that old clients (pre-6.0) can still
// authenticate with one device when multiple are registered, and that
// new clients can see all devices.
func testBackwardsCompatibility() error {
	// Simulate server response with 2 devices
	challenge := &U2FAuthenticateChallengeSimulated{
		AuthenticateChallenge: &AuthenticateChallengeSimulated{
			Version:   "U2F_V2",
			Challenge: "device1-challenge",
			KeyHandle: "device1-keyhandle",
			AppID:     "https://teleport.example.com",
		},
		Challenges: []AuthenticateChallengeSimulated{
			{
				Version:   "U2F_V2",
				Challenge: "device1-challenge",
				KeyHandle: "device1-keyhandle",
				AppID:     "https://teleport.example.com",
			},
			{
				Version:   "U2F_V2",
				Challenge: "device2-challenge",
				KeyHandle: "device2-keyhandle",
				AppID:     "https://teleport.example.com",
			},
		},
	}

	jsonData, err := json.Marshal(challenge)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to marshal challenge: %v", err)
	}

	// Scenario 1: Old client (pre-6.0) - only reads top-level fields
	var oldClientResp map[string]interface{}
	err = json.Unmarshal(jsonData, &oldClientResp)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to unmarshal for old client: %v", err)
	}

	oldClientChallenge, ok := oldClientResp["challenge"]
	if !ok {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Top-level challenge missing for old client")
	}
	if oldClientChallenge != "device1-challenge" {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Old client should get first device's challenge from top-level")
	}

	oldClientKeyHandle, ok := oldClientResp["keyHandle"]
	if !ok {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Top-level keyHandle missing for old client")
	}
	if oldClientKeyHandle != "device1-keyhandle" {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: Old client should get first device's key handle from top-level")
	}

	fmt.Println("✓ Old client (pre-6.0) can authenticate with first device")

	// Scenario 2: New client (6.0+) - should read Challenges array
	var newClientResp U2FAuthenticateChallengeSimulated
	err = json.Unmarshal(jsonData, &newClientResp)
	if err != nil {
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to unmarshal for new client: %v", err)
	}

	if len(newClientResp.Challenges) == 0 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: New client cannot see the Challenges array - multi-device auth broken!")
	}
	if len(newClientResp.Challenges) != 2 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: New client should see 2 challenges for 2 registered devices")
	}

	// New client should be able to find both devices
	hasDevice1 := false
	hasDevice2 := false
	for _, ch := range newClientResp.Challenges {
		if ch.KeyHandle == "device1-keyhandle" {
			hasDevice1 = true
		}
		if ch.KeyHandle == "device2-keyhandle" {
			hasDevice2 = true
		}
	}

	if !hasDevice1 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: New client cannot see device 1")
	}
	if !hasDevice2 {
		return fmt.Errorf("BUG: New client cannot see device 2")
	}

	fmt.Println("✓ New client (6.0+) can see all registered devices")
	fmt.Println("✓ Backwards compatibility maintained")
	return nil
}

// === SIMULATED TYPES ===
// These simulate the types from lib/auth/auth.go and lib/auth/u2f/authenticate.go

// AuthenticateChallengeSimulated simulates u2f.SignRequest from the u2f library
type AuthenticateChallengeSimulated struct {
	Version   string `json:"version"`
	Challenge string `json:"challenge"`
	KeyHandle string `json:"keyHandle"`
	AppID     string `json:"appId"`
}

// U2FAuthenticateChallengeSimulated simulates the struct in lib/auth/auth.go
type U2FAuthenticateChallengeSimulated struct {
	// Before 6.0 teleport would only send 1 U2F challenge. Embed the old
	// challenge for compatibility with older clients. All new clients should
	// ignore this and read Challenges instead.
	*AuthenticateChallengeSimulated
	// The list of U2F challenges, one for each registered device.
	Challenges []AuthenticateChallengeSimulated `json:"challenges"`
}

// === TEST SUMMARY ===
// This test demonstrates:
// 1. JSON marshaling behavior with embedded pointers
// 2. How the bug causes old clients to only see one device
// 3. How new clients might not see all devices if Challenges field isn't properly populated
// 4. The backwards compatibility mechanism that was intended to help but doesn't fully solve the multi-device problem
//
// EXPECTED OUTCOMES:
// The test will PASS if:
// - All challenges are properly preserved in JSON
// - Both embedded and array fields survive marshaling/unmarshaling
// - Backwards compatibility is maintained
//
// The test will FAIL if:
// - The Challenges array is lost during marshaling
// - Client-side unmarshaling doesn't populate the Challenges field
// - Only one device's challenge is available to new clients
//
// IMPACT OF THE BUG:
// Users with multiple U2F devices will:
// 1. Only be presented with one device challenge during login
// 2. Be unable to use their alternate devices
// 3. Experience inconsistent behavior when switching between client versions
// 4. Potentially be locked out if the one device presented is not the one they have

